# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: flash-attention
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] In machine learning, **attention** is a method that determines the importance of each component in a sequence relative to the other components in that sequence.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] In natural language processing, importance is represented by "soft" weights assigned to each word in a sentence.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] More generally, attention encodes vectors called token embeddings across a fixed-width sequence that can range from tens to millions of tokens in size.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Unlike "hard" weights, which are computed during the backwards training pass, "soft" weights exist only in the forward pass and therefore change with every step of the input.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Earlier designs implemented the attention mechanism in a serial recurrent neural network (RNN) language translation system, but a more recent design, namely the transformer, removed the slower sequential RNN and relied more heavily on the faster parallel attention scheme.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Inspired by ideas about attention in humans, the attention mechanism was developed to address the weaknesses of using information from the hidden layers of recurrent neural networks.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Recurrent neural networks favor information contained in words at the end of a sentence and thus deemed more recent, thereby tending to attenuate the significance and associated predictive weight assigned to information earlier in the sentence.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Attention allows a token equal access to any part of a sentence directly, rather than only through the previous state.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Additional surveys of the attention mechanism in deep learning are provided by Niu et al. and Soydaner.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] The major breakthrough came with self-attention, where each element in the input sequence attends to all others, enabling the model to capture global dependencies.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] This idea was central to the Transformer architecture, which replaced recurrence with attention mechanisms.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] As a result, Transformers became the foundation for models like BERT, T5 and generative pre-trained transformers (GPT).
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] The modern era of machine attention was revitalized by grafting an attention mechanism (Fig 1. orange) to an Encoder-Decoder.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Figure 2 shows the internal step-by-step operation of the attention block (A) in Fig 1.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] The diagram shows the attention forward pass calculating correlations of the word "that" with other words in "See that girl run." Given the right weights from training, the network should be able to identify "girl" as a highly correlated word.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] In translating between languages, alignment is the process of matching words from the source sentence to words of the translated sentence.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Networks that perform verbatim translation without regard to word order would show the highest scores along the (dominant) diagonal of the matrix.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] The off-diagonal dominance shows that the attention mechanism is more nuanced.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Consider an example of translating *I love you* to French.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] On the first pass through the decoder, 94% of the attention weight is on the first English word *I*, so the network offers the word *je*.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] On the second pass of the decoder, 88% of the attention weight is on the third English word *you*, so it offers *t'*.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] On the last pass, 95% of the attention weight is on the second English word *love*, so it offers *aime*.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] In the *I love you* example, the second word *love* is aligned with the third word *aime*.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Sometimes, alignment can be multiple-to-multiple.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] For example, the English phrase *look it up* corresponds to *cherchez-le*.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] For convolutional neural networks, attention mechanisms can be distinguished by the dimension on which they operate, namely: spatial attention, channel attention, or combinations.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] These variants recombine the encoder-side inputs to redistribute those effects to each target output.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Often, a correlation-style matrix of dot products provides the re-weighting coefficients.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] In the figures below, W is the matrix of context attention weights, similar to the formula in Overview section above.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] The size of the attention matrix is proportional to the square of the number of input tokens.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Therefore, when the input is long, calculating the attention matrix requires a lot of GPU memory.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Flash attention is an implementation that reduces the memory needs and increases efficiency without sacrificing accuracy.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] It achieves this by partitioning the attention computation into smaller blocks that fit into the GPU's faster on-chip memory, reducing the need to store large intermediate matrices and thus lowering memory usage while increasing computational efficiency.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] FlexAttention is an attention kernel developed by Meta that allows users to modify attention scores prior to softmax and dynamically chooses the optimal attention algorithm.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Attention is widely used in natural language processing, computer vision, and speech recognition.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] In NLP, it improves context understanding in tasks like question answering and summarization.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] In vision, visual attention helps models focus on relevant image regions, enhancing object detection and image captioning.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] From the original paper on vision transformers (ViT), visualizing attention scores as a heat map (called saliency maps or attention maps) has become an important and routine way to inspect the decision making process of ViT models.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] One can compute the attention maps with respect to any attention head at any layer, while the deeper layers tend to show more semantically meaningful visualization.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Attention rollout is a recursive algorithm to combine attention scores across all layers, by computing the dot product of successive attention maps.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Because vision transformers are typically trained in a self-supervised manner, attention maps are generally not class-sensitive.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] When a classification head is attached to the ViT backbone, class-discriminative attention maps (CDAM) combines attention maps and gradients with respect to the class `[CLS]` token.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Some class-sensitive interpretability methods originally developed for convolutional neural networks can be also applied to ViT, such as GradCAM, which back-propagates the gradients to the outputs of the final attention layer.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Using attention as basis of explanation for the transformers in language and vision is not without debate.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] While some pioneering papers analyzed and framed attention scores as explanations, higher attention scores do not always correlate with greater impact on model performances.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] The matrix Q contains m queries, while matrices $K,V$ jointly contain an *unordered* set of n key-value pairs.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Value vectors in matrix V are weighted using the weights resulting from the softmax operation, so that the rows of the m -by- $d_{v}$ output matrix are confined to the convex hull of the points in $\mathbb {R} ^{d_{v}}$ given by the rows of V .
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] To understand the permutation invariance and permutation equivariance properties of QKV attention, let $A\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times m}$ and $B\in \mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ be permutation matrices; and $D\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times n}$ an arbitrary matrix.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] These properties are inherited when applying linear transforms to the inputs and outputs of QKV attention blocks.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] For example, a simple self-attention function defined as: $X\mapsto {\text{Attention}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is permutation equivariant with respect to re-ordering the rows of the input matrix X in a non-trivial way, because every row of the output is a function of all the rows of the input.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Similar properties hold for *multi-head attention*, which is defined below.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] The softmax output, also in $\mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ is then *lower triangular*, with zeros in all elements above the diagonal.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] The masking ensures that for all $1\leq i<j\leq n$ , row i of the attention output is independent of row j of any of the three input matrices.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] The permutation invariance and equivariance properties of standard QKV attention do not hold for the masked variant.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] The permutation properties of (standard, unmasked) QKV attention apply here also.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] For permutation matrices, $A,B$ : ${\text{MultiHead}}(AQ,BK,BV)=A\,{\text{MultiHead}}(Q,K,V)$ from which we also see that multi-head self-attention: $X\mapsto {\text{MultiHead}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is equivariant with respect to re-ordering of the rows of input matrix X .
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] ${\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}(QWK^{T})V$ where W is a learnable weight matrix.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Self-attention is essentially the same as cross-attention, except that query, key, and value vectors all come from the same model.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] Both encoder and decoder can use self-attention, but with subtle differences.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] For encoder self-attention, we can start with a simple encoder without self-attention, such as an "embedding layer", which simply converts each input word into a vector by a fixed lookup table.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] This gives a sequence of hidden vectors $h_{0},h_{1},\dots$ .
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] This can be applied repeatedly, to obtain a multilayered encoder.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] This is the "encoder self-attention", sometimes called the "all-to-all attention", as the vector at every position can attend to every other.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] For decoder self-attention, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because during the autoregressive decoding process, the decoder cannot attend to future outputs that has yet to be decoded.
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] This can be solved by forcing the attention weights $w_{ij}=0$ for all $i<j$ , called "causal masking".
[src:flash-attention/attention-machine-learning] This attention mechanism is the "causally masked self-attention".
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] In computer graphics, a **shader** is a programmable operation which is applied to data as it moves through the rendering pipeline.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Shaders act on data such as vertices and primitives, generate or morph geometries and fragments, and calculate the colors in a rendered image.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Shaders can execute a wide variety of operations.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] In modern real-time computer graphics, shaders are run on graphics processing units (GPUs) - dedicated hardware which provide parallel execution of programs.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Because image rendering is an embarrassingly parallel problem (having an Amdahl's index of one), shaders benefit greatly from parallel computing, such as SIMD hardware.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] The drive for faster rendering has produced highly parallel processors, like GPUs, which are now used for general-purpose computing.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Shaders used for general purposes are commonly called *compute shaders*.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] The term "shader" was first introduced to the public by Pixar with version 3.0 of their RenderMan Interface Specification, originally published in May 1988.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] As graphics processing units evolved, major graphics software libraries such as OpenGL and Direct3D began to support shaders.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] The first shader-capable GPUs only supported pixel shading, but vertex shaders were quickly introduced once developers realized the power of shaders.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] The first video card with a programmable pixel shader was the Nvidia GeForce 3 (NV20), released in 2001.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Geometry shaders were introduced with Direct3D 10 and OpenGL 3.2.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Graphics hardware evolved toward a unified shader model, making all shaders equal.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] The traditional use of shaders is to operate on data in the graphics pipeline to control the rendering of an image.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Graphics shaders are classified according to their position in the pipeline, the data being manipulated, and the graphics API being used.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Vertex shaders are run once for each 3D vertex given to the graphics processor.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] The purpose is to transform each vertex's 3D position in virtual space to the 2D coordinate at which it appears on the screen (as well as a depth value for the Z-buffer).
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Vertex shaders can manipulate properties such as position, color and texture coordinates, but cannot create new vertices.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] The output of the vertex shader goes to the next stage in the pipeline, which is either a geometry shader if present, or the rasterizer.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Vertex shaders can enable powerful control over the details of position, movement, lighting, and color in any scene involving 3D models.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Geometry shaders were introduced in Direct3D 10 and OpenGL 3.2; formerly available in OpenGL 2.0+ with the use of extensions.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] This type of shader can generate new graphics primitives, such as points, lines, and triangles, from those primitives that were sent to the beginning of the graphics pipeline.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Geometry shader programs are executed after vertex shaders.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] They take as input a whole primitive, possibly with adjacency information.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] For example, when operating on triangles, the three vertices are the geometry shader's input.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] The shader can then emit zero or more primitives, which are rasterized and their fragments ultimately passed to a pixel shader.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Typical uses of a geometry shader include point sprite generation, geometry tessellation, shadow volume extrusion, and single pass rendering to a cube map.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] A typical real-world example of the benefits of geometry shaders would be automatic mesh complexity modification.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] A series of line strips representing control points for a curve are passed to the geometry shader and depending on the complexity required the shader can automatically generate extra lines each of which provides a better approximation of a curve.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] model rendered using fragment shaders with different outputs: solid white, applied texture, physically based shading.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Fragment shaders, also known as **pixel shaders**, compute color and other attributes of each "fragment": a unit of rendering work affecting at most a single output pixel.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] The simplest kinds of pixel shaders output one screen pixel as a color value; more complex shaders with multiple inputs/outputs are also possible.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Pixel shaders range from simply always outputting the same color, to applying a lighting value, to doing bump mapping, shadows, specular highlights, translucency and other phenomena.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] They can alter the depth of the fragment (for Z-buffering), or output more than one color if multiple render targets are active.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] In 3D graphics, a pixel shader alone cannot produce some kinds of complex effects because it operates only on a single fragment, without knowledge of a scene's geometry (i.e. vertex data).
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] However, pixel shaders do have knowledge of the screen coordinate being drawn, and can sample the screen and nearby pixels if the contents of the entire screen are passed as a texture to the shader.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] This technique can enable a wide variety of two-dimensional postprocessing effects such as blur, or edge detection/enhancement for cartoon/cel shaders.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Pixel shaders may also be applied in *intermediate* stages to any two-dimensional images—sprites or textures—in the pipeline, whereas vertex shaders always require a 3D scene.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] For instance, a pixel shader is the only kind of shader that can act as a postprocessor or filter for a video stream after it has been rasterized.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] OpenGL 4.0 and Direct3D 11 introduced a new shader class called a tessellation shader.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] The function can be related to a variety of variables, most notably the distance from the viewing camera to allow active level-of-detail scaling.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] This allows objects close to the camera to have fine detail, while further away ones can have more coarse meshes, yet seem comparable in quality.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] It also can drastically reduce required mesh bandwidth by allowing meshes to be refined once inside the shader units instead of down-sampling very complex ones from memory.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Some algorithms can up-sample any arbitrary mesh, while others allow for "hinting" in meshes to dictate the most characteristic vertices and edges.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Circa 2017, the AMD Vega microarchitecture added support for a new shader stage—primitive shaders—somewhat akin to compute shaders with access to the data necessary to process geometry.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Nvidia introduced mesh and task shaders with its Turing microarchitecture in 2018 which are also modelled after compute shaders.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Nvidia Turing is the world's first GPU microarchitecture that supports mesh shading through DirectX 12 Ultimate API, several months before Ampere RTX 30 series was released.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] In 2020, AMD and Nvidia released RDNA 2 and Ampere microarchitectures which both support mesh shading through DirectX 12 Ultimate.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] These mesh shaders allow the GPU to handle more complex algorithms, offloading more work from the CPU to the GPU, and in algorithm intense rendering, increasing the frame rate of or number of triangles in a scene by an order of magnitude.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Intel announced that Intel Arc Alchemist GPUs shipping in Q1 2022 will support mesh shaders.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Ray tracing shaders are supported by Microsoft via DirectX Raytracing, by Khronos Group via Vulkan, GLSL, and SPIR-V, by Apple via Metal.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Nvidia and AMD called the parts of the hardware responsible for executing these shaders "ray tracing cores".
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Compute kernels are routines compiled for high throughput accelerators (such as graphics processing units (GPUs), digital signal processors (DSPs), or field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs)), separate from but used by a main program (typically running on a central processing unit).
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] They may be specified by a separate programming language such as "OpenCL C", as "compute shaders" written in a shading language, or embedded directly in application code written in a high level language.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Compute kernels roughly correspond to inner loops when implementing algorithms in traditional languages (except there is no implied sequential operation), or to code passed to internal iterators.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Microsoft support this as DirectCompute.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] This single program, multiple data programming paradigm maps well to vector processors: there is an assumption that each invocation of a kernel within a batch is independent, allowing for data parallel execution.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] However, atomic operations may sometimes be used for synchronization between elements (for interdependent work), in some scenarios.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Individual invocations are given indices (in 1 or more dimensions) from which arbitrary addressing of buffer data may be performed (including scatter gather operations), so long as the non-overlapping assumption is respected.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] The Vulkan API provides the intermediate SPIR-V representation to describe *both* graphical shaders, and compute kernels in a language independent and machine independent manner.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] The intention is to facilitate language evolution and provide a more natural ability to leverage GPU compute capabilities, in line with hardware developments such as Unified Memory Architecture and Heterogeneous System Architecture.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] This allows closer cooperation between a CPU and GPU.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Much work has been done in the field of Kernel generation through LLMs as a means of optimizing code.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] KernelBench, created by the Scaling Intelligence Lab at Stanford, provides a framework to evaluate the ability of LLMs to generate efficient GPU kernels.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Cognition has created Kevin 32-B to create efficient CUDA kernels which is currently the highest performing model on KernelBench.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Tensor shaders are accelerator programs that deal with matrix operations on large arrays, a type of operation commonly used in neural network-based AI.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Tensor shaders are supported by Microsoft via DirectML, by Khronos Group via OpenVX, by Apple via Core ML, by Google via TensorFlow, by Linux Foundation via ONNX.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Nvidia and AMD called the parts of the hardware responsible for executing these shaders "tensor cores".
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Several programming languages exist specifically for writing shaders, and which is used can depend on the target environment.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] The shading language for OpenGL is GLSL, and Direct3D uses HLSL.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] The Metal framework, used by Apple devices, has its own shading language called Metal Shading Language.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Increasingly in modern graphics APIs, shaders are compiled into SPIR-V, an intermediate language, before they are distributed to the end user.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] This standard allows more flexible choice of shading language, regardless of target platform.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] First supported by Vulkan and OpenGL, SPIR-V is also being adopted by Direct3D.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] The graph is then compiled into a shader.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] In web development contexts, visual and component-based shader tools have also emerged.
[src:flash-attention/compute-kernel] Platforms such as shaders.com provide component-driven composition of shaders for integration into frontend frameworks including Vue, React, and Svelte, while tools such as Shadertoy and FragCoord.xyz focus on lower-level shader authoring and debugging.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In deep learning, the **transformer** is a family of artificial neural network architectures based on the multi-head attention mechanism, in which text is converted to numerical representations called tokens, and each token is converted into a vector via lookup from a word embedding table.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] At each layer, each token is then contextualized within the scope of the context window with other (unmasked) tokens via a parallel multi-head attention mechanism, allowing the signal for key tokens to be amplified and less important tokens to be diminished.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Because self-attention alone is permutation-invariant, transformers inject positional information, typically through positional encodings or learned positional embeddings, so token order can affect the output.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Transformers have the advantage of having no recurrent units, therefore requiring less training time than earlier recurrent neural architectures (RNNs) such as long short-term memory (LSTM).
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Later variations have been widely adopted for training large language models (LLMs) on large (language) datasets.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Modern transformer designs are commonly grouped into encoder-only, decoder-only, and encoder-decoder variants, depending on whether they are optimized for representation learning, autoregressive generation, or conditional sequence-to-sequence tasks.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The original version of the transformer architecture was proposed in the 2017 paper "Attention Is All You Need" by researchers at Google.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The predecessors of transformers were developed as an improvement over previous architectures for machine translation, but have found many applications since.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] They are used in large-scale natural language processing, computer vision (vision transformers), reinforcement learning, audio, multimodal learning, robotics, and playing chess.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] It has also led to the development of pre-trained systems, such as generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) and BERT (bidirectional encoder representations from transformers).
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] For many years, sequence modelling and generation was done by using plain recurrent neural networks (RNNs).
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] A well-cited early example was the Elman network (1990).
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In theory, the information from one token can propagate arbitrarily far down the sequence, but in practice the vanishing-gradient problem leaves the model's state at the end of a long sentence without precise, extractable information about preceding tokens.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] A key breakthrough was LSTM (originally described in a 1995 technical report and formally published in 1997), an RNN that introduced gating mechanisms to mitigate the vanishing gradient problem, allowing efficient learning of long-sequence modelling.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] One key architectural element was the use of *multiplicative gating units*, in which the outputs of some neurons modulate the outputs of others.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] These multiplicative units are conceptually distinct from the additive attention mechanism later introduced for sequence-to-sequence models.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Neural networks using multiplicative units were later called *sigma-pi networks* or *higher-order networks*.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] LSTM became the standard architecture for long sequence modelling until the 2017 publication of transformers.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] However, LSTM still used sequential processing, like most other RNNs.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Specifically, RNNs operate one token at a time from first to last; they cannot operate in parallel over all tokens in a sequence.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Modern transformers overcome this problem, but unlike RNNs, they require computation time that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The linearly scaling fast weight controller (1992) learns to compute a weight matrix for further processing depending on the input.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] One of its two networks has "fast weights" or "dynamic links" (1981).
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] A slow neural network learns by gradient descent to generate keys and values for computing the weight changes of the fast neural network which computes answers to queries.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] This was later shown to be equivalent to the unnormalized linear transformer.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The idea of encoder–decoder sequence transduction had been developed in the early 2010s; commonly cited as the originators that produced seq2seq are two concurrently published papers from 2014.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] A 380M-parameter model for machine translation uses two long short-term memories (LSTM).
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The *encoder* is an LSTM that takes in a sequence of tokens and turns it into a vector.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The *decoder* is another LSTM that converts the vector into a sequence of tokens.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Similarly, another 130M-parameter model used gated recurrent units (GRU) instead of LSTM.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Later research showed that GRUs are neither better nor worse than LSTMs for seq2seq.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] These early seq2seq models had no attention mechanism, and the state vector is accessible only after the *last* word of the source text was processed.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Although in theory such a vector retains the information about the whole original sentence, in practice the information is poorly preserved.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] This is because the input is processed sequentially by one recurrent network into a *fixed*-size output vector, which is then processed by another recurrent network into an output.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] If the input is long, then the output vector would not be able to contain all relevant information, degrading the output.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] As evidence, reversing the input sentence improved seq2seq translation.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The *RNN search* model introduced an attention mechanism to seq2seq for machine translation to solve the bottleneck problem (of the *fixed-size* output vector), allowing the model to process long-distance dependencies more easily.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The name is because it "emulates searching through a source sentence during decoding a translation".
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The relative performances were compared between global (that of *RNN search*) and local (sliding window) attention model architectures for machine translation, finding that mixed attention had higher quality than global attention, while local attention reduced translation time.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In 2016, Google Translate was revamped to Google Neural Machine Translation, which replaced the previous model based on statistical machine translation.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The new model was a seq2seq model where the encoder and the decoder were both 8 layers of bidirectional LSTM.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] It took nine months to develop, and it outperformed the statistical approach, which took ten years to develop.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Seq2seq models with attention (including self-attention) still suffered from the same issue with recurrent networks, which is that they are hard to parallelize, which prevented them from being accelerated on GPUs.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In 2016, *decomposable attention* applied a self-attention mechanism to feedforward networks, which are easy to parallelize, and achieved SOTA result in textual entailment with an order of magnitude fewer parameters than LSTMs.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] One of its authors, Jakob Uszkoreit, suspected that attention *without* recurrence would be sufficient for language translation, thus the title "attention is *all* you need".
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] That hypothesis was against conventional wisdom at the time, and even his father Hans Uszkoreit, a well-known computational linguist, was skeptical.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In the same year, self-attention (called *intra-attention or* *intra-sentence attention*) was proposed for LSTMs.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] On 2017-06-12, the original (100M-parameter) encoder–decoder transformer model was published in the "Attention is all you need" paper.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] At the time, the focus of the research was on improving seq2seq for machine translation, by removing its recurrence to process all tokens in parallel, but preserving its dot-product attention mechanism to keep its text processing performance.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] This led to the introduction of a multi-head attention model that was easier to parallelize due to the use of independent heads and the lack of recurrence.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Its parallelizability was an important factor to its widespread use in large neural networks.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] As early as spring 2017, even before the "Attention is all you need" preprint was published, one of the co-authors applied the "decoder-only" variation of the architecture to generate fictitious Wikipedia articles.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Transformer architecture is now used alongside many generative models that contribute to the ongoing AI boom.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The "reference implementation" of the original Transformer was written in a TensorFlow library.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In language modelling, ELMo (2018) was a bi-directional LSTM that produces contextualized word embeddings, improving upon the line of research from bag of words and word2vec.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] It was followed by BERT (2018), an encoder-only transformer model.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In October 2019, Google started using BERT to process search queries.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model by a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Starting in 2018, the OpenAI GPT series of decoder-only transformers became state of the art in natural language generation.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] At the end of 2022, ChatGPT, a chatbot based on a fine-tuned variant of GPT-3.5, became unexpectedly popular, triggering a boom around large language models.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Transformers have been applied in modalities beyond text.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Four days after the publication of "Attention is All You Need", a multimodal transformer architecture, MultiModel, was published by most authors of that paper.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Other examples include the vision transformer, speech recognition, robotics, and multimodal.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The vision transformer, in turn, stimulated new developments in convolutional neural networks.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The plain transformer architecture had difficulty in converging.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In the original paper, the authors recommended using learning rate warmup.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] That is, the learning rate should linearly scale up from 0 to maximal value for the first part of the training (usually recommended to be 2% of the total number of training steps), before decaying again.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] A 2020 paper found that using layer normalization *before* (instead of after) multihead attention and feedforward layers stabilizes training, not requiring learning rate warmup.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] This is the "pre-LN Transformer" and is more commonly used, compared to the original "post-LN Transformer".
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Transformers typically are first pretrained by self-supervised learning on a large generic dataset, followed by supervised fine-tuning on a small task-specific dataset.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The pretrain dataset is typically an unlabeled large corpus, such as The Pile.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The T5 transformer report documents a large number of natural language pretraining tasks.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Note that while each of these tasks is trivial or obvious for human native speakers of the language (or languages), they have typically proved challenging for previous generations of machine learning architecture.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In general, there are 3 classes of language modelling tasks: "masked", "autoregressive", and "prefixLM".
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] These classes are independent of a specific modeling architecture such as transformer, but they are often discussed in the context of transformer.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In a masked task, one or more of the tokens is masked out, and the model would produce a probability distribution predicting what the masked-out tokens are based on the context.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The loss function for the task is typically sum of log-perplexities for the masked-out tokens: ${\text{Loss}}=-\sum _{t\in {\text{masked tokens}}}\ln({\text{probability of }}t{\text{ conditional on its context}})$ and the model is trained to minimize this loss function.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The BERT series of models are trained for masked token prediction and another task.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In an autoregressive task, the entire sequence is masked at first, and the model produces a probability distribution for the first token.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Then the first token is revealed and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The loss function for the task is still typically the same.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The GPT series of models are trained by autoregressive tasks.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In a prefixLM task, the sequence is divided into two parts.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The first part is presented as context, and the model predicts the first token of the second part.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Then that would be revealed, and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The T5 series of models are trained by prefixLM tasks.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Note that "masked" as in "masked language modelling" is not "masked" as in "masked attention", and "prefixLM" as in "prefix language modeling" is not "prefixLM" as in " prefix language model".
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The following description follows exactly the transformer as described in the original paper.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] There are variants, described in the following section.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] By convention, we write all vectors as row vectors.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] For example, pushing a vector through a linear layer means multiplying it by a weight matrix on the right, as $xW$ .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] As the transformer architecture natively consists of operations over numbers (matrix multiplications, dot products, activation functions) rather than over text, there must first be a mapping from any input text to some numerical representation.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] First, the input text is treated by a *preprocessor*, which performs both textual transformations and splits the text into coarse-grained segments called *pretokens*.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The latter is referred to as *pretokenization*.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Second, each pretoken is segmented further into *tokens* by a *tokenizer* that expects to only see pretokens output by its preprocessor.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Each token it produces is a string of one or more characters belonging to a finite set of strings called the *vocabulary* V .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Third, because the vocabulary is finite and known beforehand, each token can be assigned an integer identifier, and this mapping is applied to the sequence of tokens to represent any input text as a numerical sequence.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Since this mapping is bijective, the output side can produce a sequence of integer identifiers which can then be turned back into tokens.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] After undoing some of the preprocessing, the result is again legible text.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Training a tokenizer (sometimes referred to as *vocabularization*) means finding a suitable vocabulary V , but also learning how to use it, since any given string s of length $|s|$ has $2^{|s|-1}$ hypothetical segmentations, some of which containing segments that are not in the vocabulary.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The most important hyperparameter during vocabularization is the *vocabulary size* $|V|$ : when it is small, the learned vocabulary generally consists of characters and smaller strings, and words will be segmented into many tokens.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] At larger sizes, it becomes affordable to dedicate tokens to full words, although depending on the preprocessor and tokenizer, it is not necessarily the case that large vocabularies will always use the largest token(s) available to segment a word.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Because tokens are not always full words, they may also be referred to as *subwords* and tokenization algorithms may be referred to as *subword tokenizers*.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] This is also to differentiate these systems from traditional terminology used in older information retrieval and natural language processing systems, where "tokenization" was used to denote what is today called "pretokenization" (very crudely: splitting into words).
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In tokenizers that produce tokens that are *not* part of the vocabulary, a special token that does belong to the vocabulary is used as a generic stand-in, written as "[UNK]" for "unknown".
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In principle, any string could be hidden by such an [UNK].
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Indeed, in information retrieval, pretokenizers were themselves used as tokenizers (and also called "tokenizers") with a word-level vocabulary that contained an [UNK].
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Commonly used subword tokenization algorithms are byte pair encoding (BPE) and the unigram language model (ULM), which each include a vocabularization algorithm and a dedicated segmentation algorithm.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] There also exist several segmentation algorithms that require no learning and can be applied given a vocabulary (produced by BPE or ULM, for example), like greedily recognising tokens in a pretoken by moving through it left-to-right.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Well-known software implementations of subword tokenizers are Hugging Face's `tokenizers` Python package implemented in Rust, and the `sentencepiece` Python package implemented in C++.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The latter package is named as such because one of its configuration options allows disabling the built-in pretokenizer, hence effectively making entire sentences a pretoken and thus having the tokenizer see entire sentences, rather than individual words.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Each integer token identifier is converted into an embedding vector via a lookup table.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Equivalently stated, it multiplies a one-hot representation of the token identifier by an embedding matrix M .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The dimension of an embedding vector is called *hidden size* or *embedding size* and written as $d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] This size is written as $d_{\text{model}}$ in the original transformer paper.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] An un-embedding layer is almost the reverse of an embedding layer.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Whereas an embedding layer converts a token identifier into a vector, an un-embedding layer converts a vector into a probability distribution over tokens.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The un-embedding layer is a linear-softmax layer: $\mathrm {UnEmbed} (x)=\mathrm {softmax} (xW+b)$ The matrix has shape $(d_{\text{emb}},|V|)$ .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Some architectures use the transpose of the embedding matrix M as the un-embedding matrix W in order to avoid needing double the amount of embedding-related parameters and to avoid divergence during training.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] A positional encoding is a fixed-size vector representation of the relative positions of tokens within a sequence: it provides the transformer model with information about *where* the words are in the input sequence.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] This induces a bias towards the order of the input sequence, so that, for example, the input sequence "man bites dog" is processed differently from "dog bites man".
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The positional encoding is defined as a function of type $f:\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , where d is a positive even integer.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Here, N is a free parameter that should be significantly larger than the biggest k that would be input into the positional encoding function.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The main reason for using this positional encoding function is that using it, shifts are linear transformations: $f(t+\Delta t)=\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t))f(t)$ where $\Delta t\in \mathbb {R}$ is the distance one wishes to shift.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position, and find the encoding of the position n-steps-ahead or n-steps-behind, by a matrix multiplication.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] By taking a linear sum, any convolution can also be implemented as linear transformations: $\sum _{j}c_{j}f(t+\Delta t_{j})=\left(\sum _{j}c_{j}\,\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t_{j}))\right)f(t)$ for any constants $c_{j}$ .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position and find a linear sum of the encoded locations of its neighbors.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] This sum of encoded positions, when fed into the attention mechanism, would create attention weights on its neighbors, much like what happens in a convolutional neural network language model.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In typical implementations, all operations are done over the real numbers, not the complex numbers, but since complex multiplication can be implemented as real 2-by-2 matrix multiplication, this is a mere notational difference.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Like earlier seq2seq models, the original transformer model used an **encoder–decoder** architecture.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The encoder consists of encoding layers that process all the input tokens together one layer after another, while the decoder consists of decoding layers that iteratively process the encoder's output and the decoder's output tokens so far.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The purpose of each encoder layer is to create contextualized representations of the tokens, where each representation corresponds to a token that "mixes" information from other input tokens via self-attention mechanism.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Both the encoder and decoder layers have a feed-forward neural network for additional processing of their outputs and contain residual connections and layer normalization steps.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] These feed-forward layers contain most of the parameters in a transformer model.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The feedforward network (FFN) modules in a transformer are 2-layered multilayer perceptrons: $\mathrm {FFN} (x)=\phi (xW^{(1)}+b^{(1)})W^{(2)}+b^{(2)}$ where $W^{(1)}$ and $W^{(2)}$ are weight matrices and $b^{(1)}$ and $b^{(2)}$ are bias vectors, and $\phi$ is its activation function.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The original transformer used ReLU activation.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The number of neurons in the middle layer is called *intermediate size* (GPT), *filter size* (BERT), or *feedforward size* (BERT).
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] It is typically larger than the embedding size.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] For example, in both GPT-2 series and BERT series, the intermediate size of a model is 4 times its embedding size: $d_{\text{ffn}}=4d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The attention mechanism used in the transformer architecture are scaled dot-product attention units.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] For each unit, the transformer model learns three weight matrices: the query weights $W^{Q}$ , the key weights $W^{K}$ , and the value weights $W^{V}$ .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The module takes three sequences, a query sequence, a key sequence, and a value sequence.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The query sequence is a sequence of length $\ell _{\text{seq, query}}$ , and each entry is a vector of dimension $d_{\text{emb, query}}$ .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Similarly for the key and value sequences.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] For each vector $x_{i,{\text{query}}}$ in the query sequence, it is multiplied by a matrix $W^{Q}$ to produce a query vector $q_{i}=x_{i,{\text{query}}}W^{Q}$ .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The matrix of all query vectors is the query matrix: $Q=X_{\text{query}}W^{Q}$ Similarly, we construct the key matrix $K=X_{\text{key}}W^{K}$ and the value matrix $V=X_{\text{value}}W^{V}$ .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] It is usually the case that all $W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}$ are square matrices, meaning $d_{\text{emb, query}}=d_{\text{query}}$ , etc.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Attention weights are calculated using the query and key vectors: the attention weight $a_{ij}$ from token i to token j is the dot product between $q_{i}$ and $k_{j}$ .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The attention weights are divided by the square root of the dimension of the key vectors, ${\sqrt {d_{k}}}$ , which stabilizes gradients during training, and passed through a softmax which normalizes the weights.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The fact that $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ are different matrices allows attention to be non-symmetric: if token i attends to token j (i.e. $q_{i}\cdot k_{j}$ is large), this does not necessarily mean that token j will attend to token i (i.e. $q_{j}\cdot k_{i}$ could be small).
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The output of the attention unit for token i is the weighted sum of the value vectors of all tokens, weighted by $a_{ij}$ , the attention from token i to each token.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The attention calculation for all tokens can be expressed as one large matrix calculation using the softmax function, which is useful for training due to computational matrix operation optimizations that quickly compute matrix operations.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The matrices Q , K and V are defined as the matrices where the i th rows are vectors $q_{i}$ , $k_{i}$ , and $v_{i}$ respectively.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] where the softmax is applied over each of the rows of the matrix.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The number of dimensions in a query vector is *query size* $d_{\text{query}}$ and similarly for the *key size* $d_{\text{key}}$ and *value size* $d_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The output dimension of an attention head is its *head dimension* $d_{\text{head}}$ .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The attention mechanism requires the following three equalities to hold: $\ell _{\text{seq, key}}=\ell _{\text{seq, value}},\;d_{\text{query}}=d_{\text{key}},\;d_{\text{value}}=d_{\text{head}}$ but is otherwise unconstrained.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] If the attention head is used in a self-attention fashion, then $X_{\text{query}}=X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] If the attention head is used in a cross-attention fashion, then usually $X_{\text{query}}\neq X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] It is theoretically possible for all three to be different, but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] One set of $\left(W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}\right)$ matrices is called an *attention head*, and each layer in a transformer model has multiple attention heads.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] While each attention head attends to the tokens that are relevant to each token, multiple attention heads allow the model to do this for different definitions of "relevance".
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Specifically, the query and key projection matrices, $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ , which are involved in the attention score computation, defines the "relevance".
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Meanwhile, the value projection matrix $W^{V}$ , in combination with the part of the output projection matrix $W^{O}$ , determines how the attended tokens influence what information is passed to subsequent layers and ultimately the output logits.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In addition, the scope of attention, or the range of token relationships captured by each attention head, can expand as tokens pass through successive layers.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] This allows the model to capture more complex and long-range dependencies in deeper layers.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Many transformer attention heads encode relevance relations that are meaningful to humans.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] For example, some attention heads can attend mostly to the next word, while others mainly attend from verbs to their direct objects.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The computations for each attention head can be performed in parallel, which allows for fast processing.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The outputs for the attention layer are concatenated to pass into the feedforward neural network layers.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] It is theoretically possible for each attention head to have a different head dimension $d_{\text{head}}$ , but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] As an example, in the smallest GPT-2 model, there are only self-attention mechanisms.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The transformer architecture is constructed to calculate output tokens iteratively.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Assuming $t=0$ refers to the calculation of the first output token $i=0$ , for step $t>0$ , the output token $i=0$ shall remain constant.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] This ensures properties of the model similar to autoregressive models.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Therefore, at every time step t , the calculation for all outputs i should not have access to tokens at position j for $j>=i$ (as it naturally is the case for time step $t=i$ , when tokens $j>t$ are not yet calculated).
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In words, it means that each token can pay attention to itself, and every token before it, but not any after it.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] A non-masked attention module can be thought of as a masked attention module where the mask has all entries zero.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] As an example of an uncommon use of mask matrix, the XLNet considers all masks of the form $PM_{\text{causal}}P^{-1}$ , where P is a random permutation matrix.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] An encoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple encoder layers.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Each encoder layer consists of two major components: a self-attention mechanism and a feed-forward layer.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] It takes an input as a sequence of input vectors, applies the self-attention mechanism, to produce an intermediate sequence of vectors, then applies the feed-forward layer for each vector individually.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] where ${\text{FFN}}$ stands for "feed-forward network".
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] We can more succinctly write it as ${\text{EncoderLayer}}(H)={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H))$ with the implicit convention that the ${\text{FFN}}$ is applied to each row of the matrix individually.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The first encoder layer takes the sequence of input vectors from the embedding layer, producing a sequence of vectors.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] This sequence of vectors is processed by the second encoder, and so on.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The output from the final encoder layer is then used by the decoder.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] As the encoder processes the entire input all at once, every token can attend to every other token (all-to-all attention), so there is no need for causal masking.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] A decoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple decoder layers, followed by an un-embedding layer.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Each decoder consists of three major components: a causally masked self-attention mechanism, a cross-attention mechanism, and a feed-forward neural network.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The decoder functions in a similar fashion to the encoder, but an additional attention mechanism is inserted which instead draws relevant information from the encodings generated by the encoders.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] This mechanism can also be called the *encoder–decoder attention*.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Like the first encoder, the first decoder takes positional information and embeddings of the output sequence as its input, rather than encodings.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The transformer must not use the current or future output to predict an output, so the output sequence must be partially masked to prevent this reverse information flow.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] This allows for autoregressive text generation.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] For decoding, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because a token cannot attend to tokens not yet generated.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Thus, the self-attention module in the decoder is causally masked.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In contrast, the cross-attention mechanism attends to the output vectors of the encoder, which is computed before the decoder starts decoding.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Consequently, there is no need for masking in the cross-attention mechanism.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Schematically, we have: ${\begin{aligned}H'&={\text{MaskedMultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H)\\{\text{DecoderLayer}}(H)&={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H',H^{E},H^{E}))\end{aligned}}$ where $H^{E}$ is the matrix with rows being the output vectors from the encoder.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The last decoder is followed by a final un-embedding layer to produce the output probabilities over the vocabulary.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Then, one of the tokens is sampled according to the probability, and the decoder can be run again to produce the next token, etc., autoregressively generating output text.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Each encoder layer contains 2 sublayers: the self-attention and the feedforward network.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Each decoder layer contains 3 sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, the cross-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The final points of detail are the residual connections and layer normalization, (denoted as "LayerNorm", or "LN" in the following), which while conceptually unnecessary, are necessary for numerical stability and convergence.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The residual connections are introduced to avoid vanishing gradient issues and stabilize the training process.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] They can be expressed by $x\mapsto F(x)+x$ , where F is a given component of the transformer.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Adding the input x can preserve the input information and avoid issues when the gradient of $F(x)$ is close to zero.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Similarly to how the feedforward network modules are applied individually to each vector, the LayerNorm is also applied individually to each vector.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] There are two common conventions in use: the *post-LN* and the *pre-LN* convention.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In the post-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (x))$ where $\mathrm {Sublayer} (x)$ is the function implemented by the sublayer itself.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] In the pre-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x))$ The original 2017 transformer used the post-LN convention.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] It was difficult to train and required careful hyperparameter tuning and a "warm-up" in learning rate, where it starts small and gradually increases.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The pre-LN convention, proposed several times in 2018, was found to be easier to train, requiring no warm-up, leading to faster convergence.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The transformer architecture, being modular, allows variations.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Several common variations are described here.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] An "encoder-only" transformer applies the encoder to map an input text into a sequence of vectors that represent the input text.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] This is usually used for text embedding and representation learning for downstream applications.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] They are less often used currently, as they were found to be not significantly better than training an encoder–decoder transformer, then taking just the encoder.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] They are also referred to as "all-to-all" or "BERT-like".
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] A "decoder-only" transformer is not literally decoder-only, since without an encoder, the cross-attention mechanism has nothing to attend to.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Thus, the decoder layers in a decoder-only transformer is composed of just two sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] This is usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The models in the GPT series and Chinchilla series are decoder-only.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] They are also referred to as "autoregressive" or "causal".
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] An "encoder–decoder" transformer is generally the same as the original transformer, with 2 sublayers per encoder layer and 3 sublayers per decoder layer, etc.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] They might have minor architectural improvements, such as alternative activation functions, changing the location of normalization, etc.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] This is also usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] The models in the T5 series are encoder–decoder.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] A "prefixLM" (prefix language model) is a decoder-only architecture, but with prefix masking, which is different from causal masking.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Specifically, it has mask of the form $M_{\text{prefixLM}}={\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf {0} &-\infty \\\mathbf {0} &M_{\text{causal}}\end{bmatrix}}$ where the first columns correspond to the "prefix", and the subsequent columns correspond to the autoregressively generated text based on the prefix.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] They resemble encoder–decoder models, but has less "sparsity".
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] Such models are rarely used, though they are cited as theoretical possibilities and benchmarked comparisons.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p01] For example, in 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model with a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model, as transformer-based decoders did not appear to significantly increase quality unlike the encoder, while the RNN decoder was much faster.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] The original transformer uses ReLU activation function.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Other activation functions were developed.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] The Llama series and PaLM used SwiGLU; both GPT-1 and BERT used GELU.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Alternative activation functions are often used in combination with Gated Linear Units in the feedforward module.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] The normalization used in the transformer can be different from LayerNorm.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] One example is RMSNorm which is used in the Llama series.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Other examples include ScaleNorm and FixNorm.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Transformers may use other positional encoding methods than sinusoidal.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] The original transformer paper reported using a learned positional encoding, but finding it not superior to the sinusoidal one.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Later, found that causal masking itself provides enough signal to a transformer decoder that it can learn to implicitly perform absolute positional encoding without the positional encoding module.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Then the RoPE encoding is applied to each pair of coordinates.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] The benefit of RoPE is that the dot-product between two vectors depends on their relative location only: ${\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n{\big )}={\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m+k{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n+k{\big )}$ for any integer k .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] ALiBi (Attention with Linear Biases) is not a *replacement* for the positional encoder on the original transformer.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Instead, it is an *additional* positional encoder that is directly plugged into the attention mechanism.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] The idea being that the linear bias matrix is a softened mask.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Just as 0 represent full attention paid, and $-\infty$ represents no attention paid, the linear bias matrix increases attention paid in one direction and decreases attention paid in the other direction.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] ALiBi allows pretraining on short context windows, then fine-tuning on longer context windows.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Since it is directly plugged into the attention mechanism, it can be combined with any positional encoder that is plugged into the "bottom" of the entire network (which is where the sinusoidal encoder on the original transformer, as well as RoPE and many others, are located).
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Relative Position Encodings is similar to ALiBi, but more generic: ${\begin{aligned}{\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}\left({\frac {QK^{\mathrm {T} }}{\sqrt {d_{k}}}}+B\right)V\end{aligned}}$ where B is a Toeplitz matrix, that is, $B_{i,j}=B_{i',j'}$ whenever $i-j=i'-j'$ .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] This is contrasted with the original sinusoidal positional encoding, which is an "absolute positional encoding".
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] The transformer model has been implemented in standard deep learning frameworks such as TensorFlow and PyTorch.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] *Transformers* is a library produced by Hugging Face that supplies transformer-based architectures and pretrained models.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] When an autoregressive transformer is used for inference, such as generating text, the query vector is different at each step, but the already-computed key and value vectors are always the same.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] The **KV caching** method saves the computed key and value vectors at each attention block, so that they are not recomputed at each new token.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] PagedAttention applies memory paging to KV caching.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] If a transformer is used with a baked-in prompt, such as ["You are a customer support agent..."], then the key and value vectors can be computed for the prompt, and saved on disk.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] The saving in compute is significant when the model is used for many short real-time interactions, such as in online chatbots.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] In general, when a user uses an autoregressive transformer to generate a continuation to a sequence of tokens, the model would first perform a forward-pass on this sequence, whereby the KV caches over this sequence are computed.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Hyperscalers serving large Transformer models may use **disaggregated inference**, wherein prefilling and decoding are performed on separately specialized hardware.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] FlashAttention is an algorithm that implements the transformer attention mechanism efficiently on a GPU.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] It is a communication-avoiding algorithm that performs matrix multiplications in blocks, such that each block fits within the cache of a GPU, and by careful management of the blocks it minimizes data copying between GPU caches (as data movement is slow).
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] The FlashAttention method is a communication-avoiding algorithm that fuses these operations into a single loop, increasing the arithmetic intensity.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] In practice, FlashAttention operates over multiple queries and keys per loop iteration, in a similar way as blocked matrix multiplication.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] If backpropagation is needed, then the output vectors and the intermediate arrays $[m_{1},\dots ,m_{N}],[\ell _{1},\dots ,\ell _{N}]$ are cached, and during the backward pass, attention matrices are rematerialized from these, making it a form of gradient checkpointing.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] An improved version, FlashAttention-2, was developed to cater to the rising demand for language models capable of handling longer context lengths.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] It offers enhancements in work partitioning and parallelism, enabling it to achieve up to 230 TFLOPs/s on A100 GPUs (FP16/BF16), a 2x speed increase over the original FlashAttention.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Key advancements in FlashAttention-2 include the reduction of non-matmul FLOPs, improved parallelism over the sequence length dimension, better work partitioning between GPU warps, and added support for head dimensions up to 256 and multi-query attention (MQA) and grouped-query attention (GQA).
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Benchmarks revealed FlashAttention-2 to be up to 2x faster than FlashAttention and up to 9x faster than a standard attention implementation in PyTorch.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Future developments include optimization for new hardware like H100 GPUs and new data types like FP8.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] FlashAttention-4 focuses on pipelining to increase instruction throughput, and was developed to perform particularly well on Blackwell GPUs.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Multi-Query Attention changes the Multihead Attention mechanism.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] This has a neutral effect on model quality and training speed, but increases inference speed.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] More generally, grouped-query attention (GQA) partitions attention heads into groups, each of which shares the key-value pair.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] MQA is GQA with one group, while standard Multihead Attention is GQA with the maximal number of groups.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Multihead Latent Attention (MLA) is a low-rank approximation to standard MHA.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Specifically, each hidden vector, before entering the attention mechanism, is first projected to two low-dimensional spaces ("latent space"), one for query and one for key-value (KV vector).
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] This design minimizes the KV cache, as only the low-dimensional KV vector needs to be cached.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Speculative decoding is a method to accelerate token decoding.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Similarly to speculative execution in CPUs, future tokens are computed quickly, then verified.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] If the quickly computed tokens are incorrect, they are discarded and computed slowly.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] The key factor in speculative decoding is that a transformer decoder can verify faster than it can decode, in the following sense.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Suppose we have two transformer models like GPT-3 and GPT-3-small, both with a context window size of 512.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] To generate an entire context window autoregressively with greedy decoding with GPT-3, it must be run for 512 times, each time generating a token $x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{512}$ , taking time $512T_{\text{GPT-3}}$ .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] However, if we had some educated guess for the values of these tokens, we could verify all of them in parallel, in one run of the model, by checking that each $x_{t}$ is indeed the token with the largest log-likelihood in the t -th output.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] In speculative decoding, a smaller model or some other simple heuristic is used to generate a few speculative tokens that are subsequently verified by the larger model.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] These tokens are then run through the larger GPT-3 in one go.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Suppose that ${\tilde {x}}_{1}$ and ${\tilde {x}}_{2}$ are verified by GPT-3 as what it would have picked, then those are kept, but ${\tilde {x}}_{3}$ is not, so ${\tilde {x}}_{3},{\tilde {x}}_{4}$ are discarded, and GPT-3 is run on those.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] For non-greedy decoding, similar ideas apply, except the speculative tokens are accepted or rejected stochastically, in a way that guarantees the final output distribution is the same as if speculative decoding was not used.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] In Multi-Token Prediction, a single forward pass creates a final embedding vector, which then is un-embedded into a token probability.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] However, that vector can then be further processed by another transformer block to predict the *next* token, and so on for arbitrarily many steps into the future.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] This trades off accuracy for speed, since each new token costs just one more transformer block, rather than the entire stack.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Training transformer-based architectures can be expensive, especially for long inputs.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Many methods have been developed to attempt to address the issue.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] In the image domain, Swin transformer is an efficient architecture that performs attention inside shifting windows.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] In the audio domain, SepTr decouples the attention in time and frequency domains.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] *Long Range Arena* (2020) is a standard benchmark for comparing the behavior of transformer architectures over long inputs.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] The standard attention graph is either all-to-all or causal, both of which scales as $O(N^{2})$ where N is the number of tokens in a sequence.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Reformer (2020) reduces the computational load from $O(N^{2})$ to $O(N\ln N)$ by using locality-sensitive hashing and reversible layers.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Sparse attention uses attention graphs that grows slower than $O(N^{2})$ .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] For example, BigBird (2020) uses random small-world networks which grows as $O(N)$ .
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Ordinary transformers require a memory size that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Attention-free transformers reduce this to a linear dependence while still retaining the advantages of a transformer by linking the key to the value.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Similarly for multiple queries, and for multihead attention.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] This approximation can be computed in linear time, as we can compute the matrix $\varphi (k_{i})v_{i}^{T}$ first, then multiply it with the query.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Transformers can also be used/adapted for modalities (input or output) beyond just text, usually by finding a way to "tokenize" the modality.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Multimodal models can either be trained from scratch, or by finetuning.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] A 2022 study found that transformers pretrained only on natural language can be finetuned on only 0.03% of parameters and become competitive with LSTMs on a variety of logical and visual tasks, demonstrating transfer learning.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] The LLaVA was a vision-language model composed of a language model (Vicuna-13B) and a vision model (ViT-L/14), connected by a linear layer.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Vision transformers adapt the transformer to computer vision by breaking down input images as a series of patches, turning them into vectors, and treating them like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Conformer and later Whisper follow the same pattern for speech recognition, first turning the speech signal into a spectrogram, which is then treated like an image, i.e. broken down into a series of patches, turned into vectors and treated like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Perceivers are a variant of transformers designed for multimodality.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] For image generation, notable architectures are DALL-E 1 (2021), Parti (2022), Phenaki (2023), and Muse (2023).
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Unlike later models, DALL-E is not a diffusion model.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Instead, it uses a decoder-only transformer that autoregressively generates a text, followed by the token representation of an image, which is then converted by a variational autoencoder to an image.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Parti is an encoder–decoder transformer, where the encoder processes a text prompt, and the decoder generates a token representation of an image.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] Muse is an encoder-only transformer that is trained to predict masked image tokens from unmasked image tokens.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] During generation, all input tokens are masked, and the highest-confidence predictions are included for the next iteration, until all tokens are predicted.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] It is a bidirectional masked transformer conditioned on pre-computed text tokens.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] The generated tokens are then decoded to a video.
[src:flash-attention/flashattention-p02] The transformer has had great success in natural language processing (NLP).
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] GPUs are also increasingly being used for artificial intelligence (AI) processing due to linear algebra acceleration, which is also used extensively in graphics processing.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] This contrasts with earlier graphics controllers known as video display controllers which had no internal calculation capabilities, or blitters, which performed only basic memory movement operations.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The modern GPU emerged during the 1990s, adding the ability to perform operations like drawing lines and text without CPU help, and later adding 3D functionality.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Graphics functions are generally independent and this lends these tasks to being implemented on separate calculation engines.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Modern GPUs include hundreds, or thousands, of calculation units.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] This made them useful for non-graphic calculations involving embarrassingly parallel problems due to their parallel structure.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The ability of GPUs to rapidly perform vast numbers of calculations has led to their adoption in diverse fields including artificial intelligence (AI) where they excel at handling data-intensive and computationally demanding tasks.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Other non-graphical uses include the training of neural networks and cryptocurrency mining.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Many companies have produced GPUs under a number of brand names.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In 2009, Intel, Nvidia, and AMD/ATI were the market share leaders, with 49.4%, 27.8%, and 20.6% market share respectively.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In addition, Matrox while originally producing custom solutions, now customizes GPUs from Intel and AMD for workstation usage.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Chinese companies such as Jingjia Micro have also produced GPUs for the domestic market although in terms of worldwide sales, they lag behind market leaders.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Several factors of GPU construction affect the performance of the card for real-time rendering, such as the size of the connector pathways in the semiconductor device fabrication, the clock signal frequency, and the number and size of various on-chip memory caches.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] GPU performance is typically measured in floating point operations per second (FLOPS); Modern GPUs typically deliver performance measured in teraflops (TFLOPS).
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] This is an estimated performance measure, and should not be treated as fact, as other factors can affect actual performance.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Modern GPUs also include dedicated hardware blocks for ray tracing, video encoding, and AI acceleration.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In personal computers, there are two main forms of GPUs: dedicated graphics (also called discrete graphics) and integrated graphics (also called shared graphics solutions, integrated graphics processors (IGP), or unified memory architecture (UMA).
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Technologies such as Scalable Link Interface (SLI), NVLink, and CrossFire allow multiple GPUs to draw images simultaneously for a single screen, increasing the processing power available for graphics.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] These technologies, however, are increasingly uncommon; most games do not fully use multiple GPUs, as most users cannot afford them.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Because GPU computations are memory-intensive, integrated processing may compete with the CPU for relatively slow system RAM, as it has minimal or no dedicated video memory.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] IGPUs use system memory with bandwidth up to a current maximum of 128 gigabytes per second, whereas a discrete graphics card may have a bandwidth of more than 1000 gigabytes per second between its video random access memory (VRAM) and GPU core.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] This memory bus bandwidth can limit the performance of the IGPU, though multi-channel memory can mitigate this deficiency.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] On systems with "Unified Memory Architecture" (UMA), including modern AMD processors with integrated graphics, modern Intel processors with integrated graphics, Apple processors, and modern consoles, the CPU cores and the GPU block share the same pool of RAM and memory address space.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] It is common to use a general purpose graphics processing unit (GPGPU) as a modified form of stream processor or a vector processor, running compute kernels.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] This turns the massive computational power of a modern graphics accelerator's shader pipeline into general-purpose computing power.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In certain applications requiring massive vector operations, this can yield several orders of magnitude higher performance than a conventional CPU.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The two largest discrete GPU designers, AMD and Nvidia, are pursuing this approach with an array of applications.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia and AMD collaborated with Stanford University to create a GPU-based client for the Folding@home distributed computing project for protein folding calculations.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In certain circumstances, the GPU calculates forty times faster than the CPUs traditionally used by such applications.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] GPU-based high performance computers play a significant role in large-scale modelling.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Three of the ten most powerful supercomputers in the world take advantage of GPU acceleration.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Since 2005 there has been interest in using the performance offered by GPUs for evolutionary computation in general, and for accelerating the fitness evaluation in genetic programming in particular.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Most approaches compile linear or tree programs on the host PC and transfer the executable to the GPU to be run.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Typically a performance advantage is only obtained by running the single active program simultaneously on many example problems in parallel, using the GPU's single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) architecture.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Substantial acceleration can also be obtained by not compiling the programs, and instead transferring them to the GPU, to be interpreted there.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] A GPU can be attached to some external bus of a notebook.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] PCI Express is the only bus used for this purpose.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The port may be, for example, an ExpressCard or mPCIe port (PCIe ×1, up to 5 or 2.5 gigabits per second respectively), a Thunderbolt 1, 2, or 3 port (PCIe ×4, up to 10, 20, or 40 gigabits per second respectively), a USB4 port with Thunderbolt compatibility, or an OCuLink port.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Those ports are only available on certain notebook systems. eGPU enclosures include their own power supply (PSU), because powerful GPUs can consume hundreds of watts.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Dedicated 3D graphics hardware dates back to graphic terminals such as the Adage AGT-30 from 1967 with analog matrix processors.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In 1969 Evans & Sutherland (E&S) introduced the Line Drawing System-1 (LDS-1), which was the first all-digital system to provide matrix multiplication.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1969, the low-cost graphics terminal IMLAC PDS-1 was introduced.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] It later saw use as an early 3D gaming machine with the likes of Maze War.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In the 1970s, the term "GPU" originally stood for graphics processor unit and described a programmable processing unit working independently from the CPU that was responsible for graphics manipulation and output.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In professional hardware, in 1972 PLATO IV system becomes operational at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Between around 1973 and 1978, several networked multiplayer wireframe 3D games are implemented and popularized by users of the system.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1972, the E&S Continuous Tone 1 (CT1) "Watkins box" system (consisting of an E&S LDS-2 and Shaded Picture System) is delivered to Case Western Reserve University.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] It offered the first real-time Gouraud shading.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In 1975, a joint effort between Evans & Sutherland Computer Corporation and the University of Utah's computer graphics department results in the first ever MOSFET video framebuffer, capable of color and smooth shading.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] E&S Continuous Tone 3 (CT3) system was delivered in 1977 to Lufthansa for pilot training using computer simulation.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] It was the first graphics system capable of real-time texture mapping.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Ikonas made graphics systems with 8- and 24-bit graphics and 3D acceleration in the late 70s.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Arcade system boards have used specialized 2D graphics circuits since the 1970s.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In early video game hardware, RAM for frame buffers was expensive, so video chips composited data together as the display was being scanned out on the monitor.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] A specialized barrel shifter circuit helped the CPU animate the framebuffer graphics for various 1970s arcade video games from Midway and Taito, such as *Gun Fight* (1975), *Sea Wolf* (1976), and *Space Invaders* (1978).
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The Namco Galaxian arcade system in 1979 used specialized graphics hardware that supported RGB color, multi-colored sprites, and tilemap backgrounds.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The Galaxian hardware was widely used during the golden age of arcade video games, by game companies such as Namco, Centuri, Gremlin, Irem, Konami, Midway, Nichibutsu, Sega, and Taito.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The Atari 2600 in 1977 used a video shifter called the Television Interface Adaptor.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Atari 8-bit computers (1979) had ANTIC, a video processor which interpreted instructions describing a "display list"—the way the scan lines map to specific bitmapped or character modes and where the memory is stored (so there did not need to be a contiguous frame buffer).
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] 6502 machine code subroutines could be triggered on scan lines by setting a bit on a display list instruction.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] ANTIC also supported smooth vertical and horizontal scrolling independent of the CPU.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In the 1980s significant advancements were made in professional 3D graphics hardware.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Perhaps most impactful was the 1981 development of the Geometry Engine, a VLSI vector processor ASIC designed by Jim Clark and Marc Hannah at Stanford University.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] This processor is the forerunner of modern tensor cores and other similar processors marketed for graphics and AI.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The Geometry Engine went on to be used in Silicon Graphics workstations for many years.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Silicon Graphics's first product, shipped in November 1983, was the IRIS 1000, a terminal with hardware-accelerated 3D graphics based on the Geometry Engine.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The Geometry Engine was capable of approximately 6 million operations per second.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The 1981 NEC μPD7220 was the first implementation of a personal computer graphics display processor as a single large-scale integration (LSI) integrated circuit chip.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] This enabled the design of low-cost, high-performance video graphics cards such as those from Number Nine Visual Technology.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] It became the best-known GPU until the mid-1980s.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] It was the first fully integrated VLSI (very large-scale integration) metal–oxide–semiconductor (NMOS) graphics display processor for PCs, supported up to 1024×1024 resolution, and laid the foundations for the PC graphics market.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] It was used in a number of graphics cards and was licensed for clones such as the Intel 82720, the first of Intel's graphics processing units.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The Williams Electronics arcade games *Robotron: 2084*, *Joust*, *Sinistar*, and *Bubbles*, all released in 1982, contain custom blitter chips for operating on 16-color bitmaps.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In 1984, Hitachi released the ARTC HD63484, the first major CMOS graphics processor for personal computers.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The ARTC could display up to 4K resolution when in monochrome mode.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] It was used in a number of graphics cards and terminals during the late 1980s.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In 1985, the Amiga was released with a custom graphics chip called Agnus including a blitter for bitmap manipulation, line drawing, and area fill.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] It also included a coprocessor with its own simple instruction set, that was capable of manipulating graphics hardware registers in sync with the video beam (e.g. for per-scanline palette switches, sprite multiplexing, and hardware windowing), or driving the blitter.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1985, IBM released the Professional Graphics Controller, designed by later to be Nvidia co-founder Curtis Priem, which was a rudimentary 3D card with 640 × 480 256-color graphics which used a dedicated CPU to draw graphics independently of the main system.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] It was used as the basis of cards by a number of makers (including Matrox) and its analog RGB signaling led directly to the VGA video standard.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Priem later in the 80s worked on the influential Sun Microsystems GX (also known as cgsix) accelerated 2D graphics card.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In 1986, Texas Instruments released the TMS34010, the first fully programmable graphics processor.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] It could run general-purpose code but also had a graphics-oriented instruction set.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] During 1990–1992, this chip became the basis of the Texas Instruments Graphics Architecture ("TIGA") Windows accelerator cards.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Following in 1987, the IBM 8514 graphics system was released.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] It was one of the first video cards for IBM PC compatibles that implemented fixed-function 2D primitives in electronic hardware.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Sharp's X68000, released in 1987, used a custom graphics chipset with a 65,536 color palette and hardware support for sprites, scrolling, and multiple playfields.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] It served as a development machine for Capcom's CP System arcade board.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Fujitsu's FM Towns computer, released in 1989, had support for a 16,777,216 color palette.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] For context, IBM also introduced its Video Graphics Array (VGA) display system in 1987, with a maximum resolution of 640 × 480 pixels.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Unlike 8514/A, VGA had no hardware acceleration features.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In November 1988, NEC Home Electronics announced its creation of the Video Electronics Standards Association (VESA) to develop and promote a Super VGA (SVGA) computer display standard as a successor to VGA.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Super VGA enabled graphics display resolutions up to 800 × 600 pixels, a 56% increase.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In 1988 SGI sold IRIS workstation graphics with 10-12 Geometry Engines and introduced the IrisVision add-in board for IBM MicroChannel bus (RS/6000) based on the Geometry Engine as well.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In 1988 as well, the first dedicated polygonal 3D graphics boards in arcade machines were introduced with the Namco System 21 and Taito Air System.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The 1990s again saw considerable advancements in professional workstation 3D graphics hardware from Sun Microsystems, SGI, and others.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The introduction of OpenGL by SGI in 1992 paved the way for standard hardware-independent 3D programming interfaces.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] However, by the mid and late 90s, professional hardware was being slowly eclipsed by consumer products which offered similar or even better performance, especially in regards to texture mapping, at a lower cost and on platforms familiar to end users.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In 1991, S3 Graphics introduced the *S3 86C911*, which its designers named after the Porsche 911 as an indication of the performance increase it promised.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The 86C911 spawned a variety of imitators: by 1995, all major PC graphics chip makers had added 2D acceleration support to their chips.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Fixed-function *Windows accelerators* surpassed expensive general-purpose graphics coprocessors in Windows performance, and such coprocessors faded from the PC market.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In the early- and mid-1990s, real-time 3D graphics became increasingly common in arcade, computer, and console games, which led to increasing public demand for hardware-accelerated 3D graphics.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Early examples of mass-market 3D graphics hardware can be found in arcade system boards such as the Sega Model 1, Namco System 22, and Sega Model 2, and the fifth-generation video game consoles such as the Saturn, PlayStation, and Nintendo 64.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Arcade systems such as the Sega Model 2 and SGI Onyx-based Namco Magic Edge Hornet Simulator in 1993 were capable of hardware T&L (transform, clipping, and lighting) years before appearing in consumer graphics cards.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In 1994, Sony used the term GPU (with the meaning graphics processing unit) in reference to the PlayStation console's Toshiba-designed Sony GPU.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Another early example is the Super FX chip, a RISC-based on-cartridge graphics chip used in some SNES games, notably *Doom* and *Star Fox*.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Some systems used DSPs to accelerate transformations.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Fujitsu, which worked on the Sega Model 2 arcade system, began working on integrating T&L into a single LSI solution for use in home computers in 1995; the Fujitsu Pinolite, the first 3D geometry processor for personal computers, announced in 1997.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The first hardware T&L GPU on home video game consoles was the Nintendo 64's Reality Coprocessor, released in 1996.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In 1997, Mitsubishi released the 3Dpro/2MP, a GPU capable of transformation and lighting, for workstations and Windows NT desktops; ATi used it for its FireGL 4000 graphics card, released in 1997.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The term "GPU" was coined by Sony in reference to the 32-bit Sony GPU (designed by Toshiba) in the PlayStation video game console, released in 1994.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Pixel shading is often used for bump mapping, which adds texture to make an object look shiny, dull, rough, or even round or extruded.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] With the introduction of the Nvidia GeForce 8 series and new generic stream processing units, GPUs became more generalized computing devices.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] GPGPUs were the precursors to what is now called a compute shader (e.g.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] CUDA, OpenCL, DirectCompute) and actually abused the hardware to a degree by treating the data passed to algorithms as texture maps and executing algorithms by drawing a triangle or quad with an appropriate pixel shader.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] This entails some overheads since units like the scan converter are involved where they are not needed (nor are triangle manipulations even a concern—except to invoke the pixel shader).
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's CUDA platform, first introduced in 2007, was the earliest widely adopted programming model for GPU computing.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] OpenCL is an open standard defined by the Khronos Group that allows for the development of code for both GPUs and CPUs with an emphasis on portability.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] OpenCL solutions are supported by Intel, AMD, Nvidia, and ARM, and according to a report in 2011 by Evans Data, OpenCL had become the second most popular HPC tool.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In 2010, Nvidia partnered with Audi to power their cars' dashboards, using the Tegra GPU to provide increased functionality to cars' navigation and entertainment systems.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Advances in GPU technology in cars helped advance self-driving technology.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] AMD's Radeon HD 6000 series cards were released in 2010, and in 2011 AMD released its 6000M Series discrete GPUs for mobile devices.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The Kepler line of graphics cards by Nvidia were released in 2012 and were used in the Nvidia 600 and 700 series cards.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] A feature in this GPU microarchitecture included GPU boost, a technology that adjusts the clock-speed of a video card to increase or decrease according to its power draw.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Kepler also introduced NVENC video encoding acceleration technology.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The PS4 and Xbox One were released in 2013; they both used GPUs based on AMD's Radeon HD 7850 and 7790.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's Kepler line of GPUs was followed by the Maxwell line, manufactured on the same process.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's 28 nm chips were manufactured by TSMC in Taiwan using the 28 nm process.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Compared to the 40 nm technology from the past, this manufacturing process allowed a 20 percent boost in performance while drawing less power.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Virtual reality headsets have high system requirements; manufacturers recommended the GTX 970 and the R9 290X or better at the time of their release.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Cards based on the Pascal microarchitecture were released in 2016.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The GeForce 10 series of cards are of this generation of graphics cards.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] They are made using the 16 nm manufacturing process which improves upon previous microarchitectures.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In 2018, Nvidia launched the RTX 20 series GPUs that added ray tracing cores to GPUs, allowing real time ray tracing to be performant on mass market hardware.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Polaris 11 and Polaris 10 GPUs from AMD are fabricated by a 14 nm process.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Their release resulted in a substantial increase in the performance per watt of AMD video cards.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] AMD also released the Vega GPU series for the high end market as a competitor to Nvidia's high end Pascal cards, also featuring HBM2 like the Titan V.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In 2019, AMD released the successor to their Graphics Core Next (GCN) microarchitecture/instruction set.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Dubbed RDNA, the first product featuring it was the Radeon RX 5000 series of video cards.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The company announced that the successor to the RDNA microarchitecture would be incremental (a "refresh").
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] AMD unveiled the Radeon RX 6000 series, its RDNA 2 graphics cards with support for hardware-accelerated ray tracing.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The product series, launched in late 2020, consisted of the RX 6800, RX 6800 XT, and RX 6900 XT.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The RX 6700 XT, which is based on Navi 22, was launched in early 2021.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The PlayStation 5 and Xbox Series X and Series S were released in 2020; they both use GPUs based on the RDNA 2 microarchitecture with incremental improvements and different GPU configurations in each system's implementation.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In the 2020s, GPUs have been increasingly used for calculations involving embarrassingly parallel problems, such as training of neural networks on enormous datasets that are needed for artificial intelligence large language models.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Specialized processing cores on most modern GPUs that are dedicated to deep learning provide significant FLOPS performance increases, using 4×4 matrix multiplication and division.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Early implementations, such as Nvidia's Volta microarchitecture, released in 2017, saw results of up to 128 TFLOPS in some applications.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Since then, AI acceleration cores have been a widely adopted feature in consumer and workstation microarchitectures starting with Nvidia's Turing microarchitecture in 2018, named Tensor cores.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] AMD originally implemented their equivalent "Matrix" Cores for consumers in their RDNA 3 architecture - however RDNA 4's Matrix Cores were the first to introduce FP8 acceleration - which is required to run the full FSR Redstone feature set such as Machine Learning Upscaling and Frame Generation.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] However, community made hacks on both Linux and Windows have allowed RDNA 2, 3, and competitor GPUs to run a weaker version of FSR 4 known as FSR 4 INT8.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] The PlayStation 5 Pro, launched in 2024, has customized Machine Learning cores - which focus solely on INT8 acceleration - based on RDNA 4's for PlayStation Spectral Super Resolution to enhance framerates and image quality.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Intel has implemented their equivalent "XMX" Cores in all of their Arc GPUs, starting with the Alchemist microarchitecture.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] This is used for XeSS (Xe Super Sampling), XeFG (Xe Frame Generation), and more.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] Ray tracing has also been incredibly prevalent in the 2020s with some games, such as DOOM: The Dark Ages, requiring a hardware ray tracing capable GPU to even start.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] While it does lead to worse performance and less overall accessibility, id software claimed this saved several man hours and shrinked the game by over 100 gigabytes due to the game being entirely built around ray tracing .
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] In 2013, 438.3 million GPUs were shipped globally and the forecast for 2014 was 414.2 million.
[src:flash-attention/graphics-processing-unit] However, by the third quarter of 2022, shipments of PC GPUs totaled around 75.5 million units, down 19% year-over-year.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] HBM was adopted by JEDEC as an industry standard in October 2013.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The second generation, **HBM2**, was accepted by JEDEC in January 2016.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] JEDEC officially announced the **HBM3** standard on January 27, 2022, and the **HBM4** standard in April 2025.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] In 2025, the world's largest manufacturers of HBM include SK Hynix, Samsung Electronics, and Micron Technology.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] TSMC produces the base die for HBM and is planned to be the foundry for several HBM companies in 2026.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] HBM has had an unprecedented demand increase; and in general DRAM (DDR4, DDR, and flash memory/NAND) price has in early 2026 "experienced compounded increases, some exceeding 200%, since early 2025 .. [because of] unprecedented demand coming from the AI sector ..
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] HBM is crowding out commodity DRAM capacity.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] HBM achieves higher bandwidth than DDR4 or GDDR5 while using less power, and in a substantially smaller form factor.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] This is achieved by stacking up to 32 DRAM dies and an optional base die which can include buffer circuitry and test logic.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The stack is often connected to the memory controller on a GPU or CPU through a substrate, such as a silicon interposer.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] Alternatively, the memory die could be stacked directly on the CPU or GPU chip.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] Within the stack the dies are vertically interconnected by through-silicon vias (TSVs) and microbumps.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The HBM technology is similar in principle to, but incompatible with, the Hybrid Memory Cube (HMC) interface developed by Micron Technology.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The HBM memory bus is very wide in comparison to other DRAM memories such as DDR4 or GDDR5.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] A HBM1 stack of four DRAM dies (4‑Hi) has two 128‑bit channels per die for a total of 8 channels and a width of 1024 bits in total.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] A graphics card/GPU with four 4‑Hi HBM stacks would therefore have a memory bus with a width of 4096 bits.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] In comparison, the bus width of GDDR memories is 32 bits, with 16 channels for a graphics card with a 512‑bit memory interface.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The larger number of connections to the memory, relative to DDR4 or GDDR5, required a new method of connecting the HBM memory to the GPU (or other processor).
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] AMD and Nvidia have both used purpose-built silicon chips, called *interposers*, to connect the memory and GPU.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] This interposer has the added advantage of requiring the memory and processor to be physically close, decreasing memory paths.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] However, as semiconductor device fabrication is significantly more expensive than printed circuit board manufacture, this adds cost to the final product.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The HBM DRAM is tightly coupled to the host compute die with a distributed interface.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The interface is divided into independent channels.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The channels are completely independent of one another and are not necessarily synchronous to each other.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] HBM DRAM uses a wide-interface architecture to achieve high-speed, low-power operation.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] HBM1 DRAM used a 500 MHz differential clock CK_t / CK_c (where the suffix "_t" denotes the "true", or "positive", component of the differential pair, and "_c" stands for the "complementary" one).
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] Commands are registered at the rising edges of CK_t and CK_c.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] Each channel interface maintained a 128‑bit data bus operating at this double data rate (DDR).
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] HBM1 supported transfer rates of 1 GT/s per pin (transferring 1 bit), yielding an overall package bandwidth of 128 GB/s.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The second generation of High Bandwidth Memory, HBM2, also specified up to eight dies per stack and doubled pin transfer rates up to 2 GT/s.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] Retaining 1024‑bit wide access, HBM2 was able to reach 256 GB/s memory bandwidth per package.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The HBM2 spec allowed up to 8 GB per package.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] HBM2 was predicted to be especially useful for performance-sensitive consumer applications such as virtual reality.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] On January 19, 2016, Samsung announced early mass production of HBM2, at up to 8 GB per stack.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] SK Hynix also announced availability of 4 GB stacks in August 2016.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] In late 2018, JEDEC announced an update to the HBM2 specification, providing for increased bandwidth and capacities.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] Up to 307 GB/s per stack (2.5 Tbit/s effective data rate) was then supported in the official specification, though products operating at this speed had already been available.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] Additionally, the update added support for 12‑Hi stacks (12 dies) making capacities of up to 24 GB per stack possible.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] On March 20, 2019, Samsung announced their Flashbolt HBM2E, featuring eight dies per stack, a transfer rate of 3.2 GT/s, providing a total of 16 GB and 410 GB/s per stack.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] August 12, 2019, SK Hynix announced their HBM2E, featuring eight dies per stack, a transfer rate of 3.6 GT/s, providing a total of 16 GB and 460 GB/s per stack.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] On July 2, 2020, SK Hynix announced that mass production has begun.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] In October 2019, Samsung announced their 12-layered HBM2E.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] In late 2020, Micron unveiled that the HBM2E standard would be updated and alongside that they unveiled the then next standard known as HBMnext (later renamed to HBM3).
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] This was to be a big generational leap from HBM2 and the replacement to HBM2E.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] This new VRAM would have come to the market in the Q4 of 2022.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] This would likely have introduce a new architecture as the naming suggests.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] While the architecture might have been overhauled, leaks pointed to performance similar to the updated HBM2E standard.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] This RAM was likely to be used mostly in data center GPUs.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] In mid 2021, SK Hynix unveiled some specifications of the HBM3 standard, with 5.2 Gbit/s I/O speeds and bandwidth of 665 GB/s per package, as well as up to 16-high 2.5D and 3D solutions.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] On 20 October 2021, before the JEDEC standard for HBM3 was finalised, SK Hynix was the first memory vendor to announce that it had finished development of HBM3 memory devices.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] According to SK Hynix, the memory would have run as fast as 6.4 Gbit/s/pin, double the data rate of JEDEC-standard HBM2E, which formally topped out at 3.2 Gbit/s/pin, or 78% faster than SK Hynix's own 3.6 Gbit/s/pin HBM2E.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The devices supported a data transfer rate of 6.4 Gbit/s and therefore a single HBM3 stack might have provided a bandwidth of up to 819 GB/s.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The basic bus widths for HBM3 remained unchanged, with a single stack of memory being 1024-bits wide.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] SK Hynix would offer this memory in two capacities: 16 GB and 24 GB, aligning with 8-Hi and 12-Hi stacks respectively.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The stacks consisted of 8 or 12 16 Gb DRAMs that are each 30 μm thick and interconnected using Through Silicon Vias (TSVs).
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] According to Anton Shilov of *Tom's Hardware*, high-performance compute GPUs or FPGAs typically used four or six HBM stacks, so with SK Hynix's HBM3 24 GB stacks they would accordingly get 3.2 TB/s or 4.9 TB/s of memory bandwidth.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] He also noted that SK Hynix's HBM3 chips were square, not rectangular like HBM2 and HBM2E chips.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] According to Chris Mellor of *The Register*, with JEDEC not yet having developed its HBM3 standard, might have meant that SK Hynix would have needed to retrofit its design to a future and faster one.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] JEDEC officially announced the HBM3 standard on January 27, 2022.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The number of memory channels was doubled from 8 channels of 128 bits with HBM2e to 16 channels of 64 bits with HBM3.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] Therefore, the total number of data pins of the interface was still 1024.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] In June 2022, SK Hynix announced they started mass production of industry's first HBM3 memory to be used with Nvidia's H100 GPU expected to ship in Q3 2022.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The memory would provide H100 with "up to 819 GB/s" of memory bandwidth.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] In August 2022, Nvidia announced that its "Hopper" H100 GPU would ship with five active HBM3 sites (out of six on board) offering 80 GB of RAM and 3 TB/s of memory bandwidth (16 GB and 600 GB/s per site).
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] On 30 May 2023, SK Hynix unveiled its HBM3E memory with 8 Gbit/s/pin data processing speed (25% faster than HBM3), which was to enter production in the first half of 2024.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] At 8 GT/s with 1024-bit bus, its bandwidth per stack is increased from 819.2 GB/s as in HBM3 to 1 TB/s.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] On 26 July 2023, Micron announced its HBM3E memory with 9.6 Gbit/s/pin data processing speed (50% faster than HBM3).
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] Micron HBM3E memory was a high-performance HBM that used 1β DRAM process technology and advanced packaging to achieve the highest performance, capacity and power efficiency in the industry.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] It could store 24 GB per 8-high cube and allowed data transfer at 1.2 TB/s.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] There would be a 12-high cube with 36 GB capacity in 2024.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] In August 2023, Nvidia announced a new version of their GH200 Grace Hopper superchip that utilized 141 GB (144 GiB physical) of HBM3e over a 6144-bit bus providing 50% higher memory bandwidth and 75% higher memory capacity over the HBM3 version.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] In May 2023, Samsung announced HBM3P with up to 7.2 Gbit/s which would be in production in 2024.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] On October 20, 2023, Samsung announced their HBM3E "Shinebolt" with up to 9.8 Gbit/s memory.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] On February 26, 2024, Micron announced the mass production of Micron's HBM3E memory.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] On March 19, 2024, SK Hynix announced the mass production of SK Hynix's HBM3E memory.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] In September 2024, SK Hynix announced the mass production of its 12-layered HBM3E memory and in November the 16-layered version.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] In February 2021, Samsung announced the development of HBM with processing-in-memory (PIM).
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] This new memory brings AI computing capabilities inside the memory, to increase the large-scale processing of data.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] A DRAM-optimised AI engine is placed inside each memory bank to enable parallel processing and minimise data movement.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] Samsung claims this will deliver twice the system performance and reduce energy consumption by more than 70%, while not requiring any hardware or software changes to the rest of the system.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] In July 2024, JEDEC announced its preliminary specifications for HBM4.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] It lowered the data rate per pin to 6.4 Gbit/s/pin (the level of HBM3) but since it now uses a 2048-bit interface per stack (doubling that of the previous generations), it still achieves greater (1.6TB/s) data rate per stack than HBM3E.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] It will also allow 4GB layers (yielding 64GB in 16-layer configurations).
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] In April 2025, JEDEC released the official HBM4 specification.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] It supports transfer speeds of up to 8 Gb/s across a 2048-bit interface, with total bandwidth of up to 2 TB/s, and stack height of 4 to 16, with DRAM die densities of 24Gb or 32Gb, allowing for capacities up to 64GB.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] HBM4 is backwards compatible with HBM3 controllers.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] Samsung, Micron, and SK hynix contributed to the standard.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] Die-stacked memory was initially commercialized in the flash memory industry.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] Toshiba introduced a NAND flash memory chip with eight stacked dies in April 2007, followed by Hynix Semiconductor introducing a NAND flash chip with 24 stacked dies in September 2007.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] 3D-stacked random-access memory (RAM) using through-silicon via (TSV) technology was commercialized by Elpida Memory, which developed the first 8 GB DRAM chip (stacked with four DDR3 SDRAM dies) in September 2009, and released it in June 2011.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] In 2011, SK Hynix introduced 16 GB DDR3 memory (40 nm class) using TSV technology, Samsung Electronics introduced 3D-stacked 32 GB DDR3 (30 nm class) based on TSV in September, and then Samsung and Micron Technology announced TSV-based Hybrid Memory Cube (HMC) technology in October.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] JEDEC first released the JESD229 standard for Wide IO memory, the predecessor of HBM featuring four 128 bit channels with single data rate clocking, in December 2011 after several years of work.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The first HBM standard JESD235 followed in October 2013.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The development of High Bandwidth Memory began at AMD in 2008 to solve the problem of ever-increasing power usage and form factor of computer memory.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] Over the next several years, AMD developed procedures to solve die-stacking problems with a team led by Senior AMD Fellow Bryan Black.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The development of HBM was completed in 2013, when SK Hynix built the first HBM memory chip.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] HBM was adopted as industry standard JESD235 by JEDEC in October 2013, following a proposal by AMD and SK Hynix in 2010.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] High volume manufacturing began at a Hynix facility in Icheon, South Korea, in 2015.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The first GPU utilizing HBM was the AMD Fiji which was released in June 2015 powering the AMD Radeon R9 Fury X.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] In January 2016, Samsung Electronics began early mass production of HBM2.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The same month, HBM2 was accepted by JEDEC as standard JESD235a.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] The first GPU chip utilizing HBM2 is the Nvidia Tesla P100 which was officially announced in April 2016.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] In June 2016, Intel released a family of Xeon Phi processors with 8 stacks of HCDRAM, Micron's version of HBM.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] At Hot Chips in August 2016, both Samsung and Hynix announced a new generation HBM memory technologies.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] Both companies announced high performance products expected to have increased density, increased bandwidth, and lower power consumption.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] Samsung also announced a lower-cost version of HBM under development targeting mass markets.
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] Removing the buffer die and decreasing the number of TSVs lowers cost, though at the expense of a decreased overall bandwidth (200 GB/s).
[src:flash-attention/high-bandwidth-memory] Nvidia's P100 and H100 GPU were the first products to utilize HBM2 and HBM3 memory, respectively; AMD's MI430X is the first to utilize HBM4.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] In computer architecture, the **memory hierarchy** separates computer storage into a hierarchy based on response time.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] Since response time, complexity, and capacity are related, the levels may also be distinguished by their performance and controlling technologies.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] Memory hierarchy affects performance in computer architectural design, algorithm predictions, and lower level programming constructs involving locality of reference.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] Designing for high performance requires considering the restrictions of the memory hierarchy, i.e. the size and capabilities of each component.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] Each of the various components can be viewed as part of a hierarchy of memories (*m*1, *m*2, ..., *mn*) in which each member mi is typically smaller and faster than the next highest member *m**i*+1 of the hierarchy.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] To limit waiting by higher levels, a lower level will respond by filling a buffer and then signaling for activating the transfer.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] This is a general memory hierarchy structuring.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] For example, a paging algorithm may be considered as a level for virtual memory when designing a computer architecture, and one can include a level of nearline storage between online and offline storage.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] The number of levels in the memory hierarchy and the performance at each level has increased over time.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] The type of memory or storage components also change historically.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] Some CPUs include additional levels of cache between L3 and memory.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] For example, the Haswell microarchitecture includes an L4 cache of 128 MB on mobile units.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] The lower levels of the hierarchy – from mass storage downwards – are also known as tiered storage.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] For example, always-on spinning disks are online, while spinning disks that spin down, such as massive arrays of idle disk (MAID), are nearline.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] Removable media such as tape cartridges that can be automatically loaded, as in a tape library, are nearline, while cartridges that must be manually loaded are offline.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] Most modern CPUs are so fast that, for most program workloads, the bottleneck is the locality of reference of memory accesses and the efficiency of the caching and memory transfer between different levels of the hierarchy.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] As a result, the CPU spends much of its time idling, waiting for memory I/O to complete.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] This is sometimes called the *space cost*, as a larger memory object is more likely to overflow a small and fast level and require use of a larger, slower level.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] The resulting load on memory use is known as *pressure* (respectively *register pressure*, *cache pressure*, and (main) *memory pressure*).
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] Modern programming languages mainly assume two levels of memory, main (*working*) memory and mass storage.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] The exception is the relatively low-level assembly language and in the inline assemblers of higher-level languages such as C where "prefetch" instructions can be used to preload the cache.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] Many programmers assume one level of memory.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] This works fine until the application hits a performance wall.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] At that point, the programmer needs to change the code's memory access patterns to that it works well with cache resources.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] A classic illustration of the effect of locality and caching is in the form of changing the order of iterating a three-dimensional array.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] *Computer Systems: A Programmer's Perspective* is a classic textbook that deals with this aspect of systems programming.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] Memory tiering is implemented on Linux as an extension to NUMA, where each memory provider has a CPU-less NUMA node with an appropriate "abstract distance" reflecting its performance.
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] The existing scheme for migrating memory between NUMA nodes using "hotness" indicated by page faults is adapted to tiering by Huang Ying (Al Maruf's TPP scheme is not in Linux mainline).
[src:flash-attention/memory-hierarchy] It also uses a weighted-interleave allocation policy.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The **softmax function,** also known as **softargmax** or **normalized exponential function**, converts a tuple of K real numbers into a probability distribution over K possible outcomes.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] It is a generalization of the logistic function to multiple dimensions, and is used in multinomial logistic regression.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The softmax function is often used as the last activation function of a neural network to normalize the output of a network to a probability distribution over predicted output classes.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The softmax function takes as input a tuple z of K real numbers, and normalizes it into a probability distribution consisting of K probabilities proportional to the exponentials of the input numbers.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] That is, prior to applying softmax, some tuple components could be negative, or greater than one; and might not sum to 1; but after applying softmax, each component will be in the interval $(0,1)$ , and the components will add up to 1, so that they can be interpreted as probabilities.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] Furthermore, the larger input components will correspond to larger probabilities.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] In words, the softmax applies the standard exponential function to each element $z_{i}$ of the input tuple $\mathbf {z}$ (consisting of K real numbers), and normalizes these values by dividing by the sum of all these exponentials.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The normalization ensures that the sum of the components of the output vector $\sigma (\mathbf {z} )$ is 1.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The term "softmax" derives from the amplifying effects of the exponential on any maxima in the input tuple.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] For example, the standard softmax of $(1,2,8)$ is approximately $(0.001,0.002,0.997)$ , which amounts to assigning almost all of the total unit weight in the result to the position of the tuple's maximal element (of 8).
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] In general, instead of e a different base b > 0 can be used.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] As above, if b > 1 then larger input components will result in larger output probabilities, and increasing the value of b will create probability distributions that are more concentrated around the positions of the largest input values.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] Conversely, if 0 < b < 1 then smaller input components will result in larger output probabilities, and decreasing the value of b will create probability distributions that are more concentrated around the positions of the smallest input values.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] A value proportional to the reciprocal of β is sometimes referred to as the *temperature*: ${\textstyle \beta =1/kT}$ , where k is typically 1 or the Boltzmann constant and T is the temperature.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] A higher temperature results in a more uniform output distribution (i.e. with higher entropy; it is "more random"), while a lower temperature results in a sharper output distribution, with one value dominating.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] In some fields, the base is fixed, corresponding to a fixed scale, while in others the parameter β (or T) is varied.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The softmax function is a multiple-variable generalization of the logistic function.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The Softmax function is a smooth approximation to the arg max function: the function whose value is the *index* of a tuple's largest element.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] Softmax is not a smooth maximum (that is, a smooth approximation to the maximum function).
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The term "softmax" is also used for the closely related LogSumExp function, which is a smooth maximum.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] For this reason, some prefer the more accurate term "softargmax", though the term "softmax" is conventional in machine learning.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] This section uses the term "softargmax" for clarity.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] For example, in this encoding $\operatorname {arg\,max} (1,5,10)=(0,0,1),$ since the third argument is the maximum.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] This can be generalized to multiple arg max values (multiple equal $z_{i}$ being the maximum) by dividing the 1 between all max args; formally 1/k where k is the number of arguments assuming the maximum.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] With the last expression given in the introduction, softargmax is now a smooth approximation of arg max: as ⁠ $\beta \to \infty$ ⁠, softargmax converges to arg max.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] In fact, softargmax is continuous, but arg max is not continuous at the singular set where two coordinates are equal, while the uniform limit of continuous functions is continuous.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The reason it fails to converge uniformly is that for inputs where two coordinates are almost equal (and one is the maximum), the arg max is the index of one or the other, so a small change in input yields a large change in output.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] However, softargmax does converge compactly on the non-singular set.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] Conversely, as ⁠ $\beta \to -\infty$ ⁠, softargmax converges to arg min in the same way, where here the singular set is points with two arg *min* values.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] It is also the case that, for any fixed β, if one input ⁠ $z_{i}$ ⁠ is much larger than the others *relative* to the temperature, $T=1/\beta$ , the output is approximately the arg max.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The softmax function is used in various multiclass classification methods, such as multinomial logistic regression (also known as softmax regression), multiclass linear discriminant analysis, naive Bayes classifiers, and artificial neural networks.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The operation is equivalent to applying a linear operator defined by $\mathbf {w}$ to tuples $\mathbf {x}$ , thus transforming the original, probably highly-dimensional, input to vectors in a K-dimensional space $\mathbb {R} ^{K}$ .
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The standard softmax function is often used in the final layer of a neural network-based classifier.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] Such networks are commonly trained under a log loss (or cross-entropy) regime, giving a non-linear variant of multinomial logistic regression.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] Here, the Kronecker delta is used for simplicity (cf. the derivative of a sigmoid function, being expressed via the function itself).
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] To ensure stable numerical computations subtracting the maximum value from the input tuple is common.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] This approach, while not altering the output or the derivative theoretically, enhances stability by directly controlling the maximum exponent value computed.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] If the function is scaled with the parameter $\beta$ , then these expressions must be multiplied by $\beta$ .
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] See multinomial logit for a probability model which uses the softmax activation function.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] In the field of reinforcement learning, a softmax function can be used to convert values into action probabilities.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] where the action value $q_{t}(a)$ corresponds to the expected reward of following action a and $\tau$ is called a temperature parameter (in allusion to statistical mechanics).
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] For high temperatures ( $\tau \to \infty$ ), all actions have nearly the same probability and the lower the temperature, the more expected rewards affect the probability.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] For a low temperature ( $\tau \to 0^{+}$ ), the probability of the action with the highest expected reward tends to 1.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] In neural network applications, the number K of possible outcomes is often large, e.g. in case of neural language models that predict the most likely outcome out of a vocabulary which might contain millions of possible words.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] This can make the calculations for the softmax layer (i.e. the matrix multiplications to determine the $z_{i}$ , followed by the application of the softmax function itself) computationally expensive.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] What's more, the gradient descent backpropagation method for training such a neural network involves calculating the softmax for every training example, and the number of training examples can also become large.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The computational effort for the softmax became a major limiting factor in the development of larger neural language models, motivating various remedies to reduce training times.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] Approaches that reorganize the softmax layer for more efficient calculation include the **hierarchical softmax** and the **differentiated softmax**.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The hierarchical softmax (introduced by Morin and Bengio in 2005) uses a binary tree structure where the outcomes (vocabulary words) are the leaves and the intermediate nodes are suitably selected "classes" of outcomes, forming latent variables.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The desired probability (softmax value) of a leaf (outcome) can then be calculated as the product of the probabilities of all nodes on the path from the root to that leaf.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] Ideally, when the tree is balanced, this would reduce the computational complexity from $O(K)$ to $O(\log _{2}K)$ .
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] In practice, results depend on choosing a good strategy for clustering the outcomes into classes.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] A Huffman tree was used for this in Google's word2vec models (introduced in 2013) to achieve scalability.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] A second kind of remedies is based on approximating the softmax (during training) with modified loss functions that avoid the calculation of the full normalization factor.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] These include methods that restrict the normalization sum to a sample of outcomes (e.g.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The standard softmax is numerically unstable because of large exponentiations.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] Subtracting by it guarantees that the exponentiations result in at most 1, see translation invariance in the mathematical properties.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] It can be efficiently computed on a GPU cluster using the FlashAttention algorithm.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] Along the main diagonal $(x,\,x,\,\dots ,\,x),$ softmax is just the uniform distribution on outputs, $(1/n,\dots ,1/n)$ : equal scores yield equal probabilities.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] Geometrically, softmax is constant along diagonals: this is the dimension that is eliminated, and corresponds to the softmax output being independent of a translation in the input scores (a choice of 0 score).
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] By contrast, softmax is not invariant under scaling.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The standard logistic function is the special case for a 1-dimensional axis in 2-dimensional space, say the *x*-axis in the (x, y) plane.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The softmax function was used in statistical mechanics as the Boltzmann distribution in the foundational paper Boltzmann (1868), formalized and popularized in the influential textbook Gibbs (1902).
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The use of the softmax in decision theory is credited to R.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] Duncan Luce, who used the axiom of independence of irrelevant alternatives in rational choice theory to deduce the softmax in Luce's choice axiom for relative preferences.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] In machine learning, the term "softmax" is credited to John S.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The output has most of its weight where the "4" was in the original input.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] This is what the function is normally used for: to highlight the largest values and suppress values which are significantly below the maximum value.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] But note: a change of *temperature* changes the output.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] This shows that high temperatures de-emphasize the maximum value.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] The softmax function generates probability predictions densely distributed over its support.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] Other functions like sparsemax or α-entmax can be used when sparse probability predictions are desired.
[src:flash-attention/softmax-function] Also the Gumbel-softmax reparametrization trick can be used when sampling from a discrete-discrete distribution needs to be mimicked in a differentiable manner.
